Title: Overview of Processes
Content:
• Process is a program in execution
• Also referred to as jobs or tasks
• Program is passive; process is active

Title: Processes Overview
Chrome Application Instances
Content:
• Multiple instances of chrome.exe running;
• Different file sizes and memory usage indicated.

Title: Overview of Process Resources
Content:
• Essential resources for a process include CPU, memory, and files
• Current activity status is tracked by Program Counter and registers
• Memory sections: Text section for program code; Data section for global variables; Stack for parameters and return addresses; Heap for dynamic memory allocation with malloc() and free()

Title: Storage Device Hierarchy
Content:
• Types of storage: primary, secondary, tertiary
• Key attributes: storage capacity, access time
• Categories: volatile and nonvolatile storage
• Examples of storage: registers, cache, main memory, hard disk drives, optical disks, magnetic tapes

Title: Stack Frames in Procedures
Content:
• Stack frames are created for each procedure call
• By the time Sub3 is called, there are three stack frames on the stack:
• The structure of the stack includes frames for Sub2, Sub3, etc.

Title: Memory Layout of C Program
Content:
• Global data section divided into initialized and uninitialized data
• Separate section for argc and argv parameters

Title: Memory Layout in C
Content:
• Includes high and low memory regions
• Components: stack, heap, uninitialized data, initialized data, text
• Example code showing memory allocation and usage

Title: Memory Layout Overview
Content:
• Size of executable segments
• Components: text, data, bss
• Decimal and hexadecimal sizes of sections

Title: Process States in Execution
Content:
• new: The process is being created
• running: Instructions are being executed
• waiting: The process is waiting for some event to occur
• ready: The process is waiting to be assigned to a processor
• terminated: The process has finished execution
• Only one process can be on a core; many processes may be ready or waiting

Title: Process Control Block Overview
Content:
• OS maintains a data structure for each process called Process Control Block (PCB) / Process Descriptor
• PCB keeps important information associated with each process
• Information includes process state, program counter, CPU registers, scheduling info (priority), memory management, and accounting data

Title: Process Control Block (PCB)
Content:
• process state
• process number
• program counter
• registers
• memory limits
• list of open files

Title: Process Representation in Linux
Content:
• Represented by the C structure task_struct
• Contains process ID (pid) and state
• Includes parent and child process structures
• Maintains a list of open files
• Holds address space information of the process
• References currently executing process

Title: Process Scheduling Overview
Content:
• Definition of process scheduler (CPU scheduler)
• Selects ready processes for execution on a CPU core
• Degree of multiprogramming indicates number of processes in memory

Title: Scheduling Queues in OS
Content:
• OS maintains scheduling queues of processes
• Ready queue contains processes ready to execute
• Waiting queues for processes waiting on events (e.g., I/O completion)
• Processes migrate between the ready queue and various wait queues

Title: Queuing and Process Scheduling
Content:
• Process execution events lead to Queuing
• I/O request places process in I/O wait queue
• Creating a child process puts it in wait queue for termination
• Interrupts remove process to interrupt wait queue

Title: Queuing Diagram Overview
Content:
• Represents process scheduling
• Components: ready queue, wait queue, free PCB
• Events: child terminates, interruption occurs, timeslice expired
• Actions: create child process, request for resources, termination

Title: CPU Scheduling Overview
Content:
• CPU scheduler selects a process from the ready queue
• Allocates a CPU core to the selected process
• Refer to the next two slides for more details

Title: CPU Scheduling Frequency
Content:
• CPU scheduler is invoked very frequently
• At least once every 100 milliseconds
• Cannot be invoked too frequently

Title: Swapping in CPU Scheduling
Content:
• Removes processes from memory when memory space is not enough
• Reduces the degree of multiprogramming
• Processes can be re-introduced into memory later
• Increases the degree of multiprogramming

Title: Context Switching in OS
Content:
• CPU switches from one process to another
• OS saves the state of the old process in its PCB
• OS restores the saved state of the new process from PCB

Title: Storage Device Hierarchy
Content:
• Types of storage: primary, secondary, tertiary
• Storage capacities vary
• Access times differ between types
• Role of volatile vs. non-volatile memory
• Examples: hard disk drives, optical disks, magnetic tapes

Title: Context Switching Essentials
Content:
• CPU registers (including Program Counter) are involved
• Memory areas are utilized during context switching
• Various tables contribute to the process environment
• These elements constitute the context of a process

Title: 儲存與復原state的原因
Content:
• 方便回溯到之前的狀態
• 可以應對意外錯誤或崩潰
• 增加系統的穩定性和可靠性

Title: Process Context Switching
Content:
• 切換ProcessB需要儲存當前process的state
• 需復原即將執行的process的state
• 儲存的state記錄在PCB當中

Title: Context Switching Process
Content:
• Saving process state
• Updating program counter
• Restoring process state

Title: Context Switch Overview
Content:
• Context switch time overhead
• System executes user applications while switching
• Hardware support reduces context switch overhead
• Special instructions exist for saving/loading all registers
• Example: Sun UltraSPARC provides multiple sets of registers
• Context switch changes to use the current register set

Title: 旗標處理
Content:
• 使用 PUSHFD 和 POPFD 操作來管理32位標誌寄存器
• PUSHAD 和 POPAD 用於16位寄存器
• 將標誌寄存器推入堆疊以保存狀態
• 從堆疊彈出標誌寄存器以恢復狀態

Title: Multiple Sets of Registers
Content:
• Multiple sets of registers facilitate context switching
• Each process has its own register values
• Reduces time needed for context switching

Content:

• Windows 或 Shell in Linux 建立新進程
• OS 負責創建及執行應用程式

Title: Process Creation Overview
Content:
• A process can create several new processes
• The creating process is called the parent
• The new processes are called children
• Forms a tree structure of processes

Title: Process Creation in Linux
Content:
• Parent and children execute concurrently or parent waits for children to terminate
• wait() system call in Linux for waiting on child processes
• Child process is a duplicate of the parent or has a new program loaded
• fork() system call creates a new process in Linux
• exec() system call replaces the process's memory space with a new program in Linux

Title: UNIX Process Creation
Content:
• Each process has a unique process ID (PID) 
• A new process is created by the fork() system call 
• The new (child) process replicates the address space of the parent process 
• Child and parent continue execution after the fork() system call 
• Return value of fork() is 0 for the child process; PID of the child for the parent process 
• The execlp() system call is used to load a new binary file into memory, destroying the old code

Title: Process Management Concepts
Content:
• Use of fork() to create a new process
• Handling errors in fork() with error messages
• Executing a command in child process using execlp
• Parent process waits for child to complete

Title: Process Termination Overview
Content:
• Process invokes exit() system call
• Returns status value and process identifier to parent
• Parent uses wait() system call to obtain status value and child's process identifier
• Necessary includes: <sys/wait.h>, <stdlib.h>

Title: Process Termination in Linux
Content:
• Terminated process becomes a zombie until parent calls wait()
• Zombie stores exit status in process control block (PCB)
• If parent does not invoke wait(), child becomes an orphan
• Orphan's parent is set to init process which periodically calls wait() to collect exit status

Title: Cooperating Processes
Content:
• Processes may share data with each other
• Example: for information sharing

Title: Interprocess Communication (IPC)
Content:
• Mechanism for cooperating processes
• Two common models: Message passing; Shared memory

Title: Communication Models
Content:
• Message Passing: involves processes communicating through a message queue
• Shared Memory: involves processes communicating through shared memory segment
• Process A and Process B can use either method to exchange information

Title: Comparisons of IPC Methods
Content:
• Message passing is useful for exchanging smaller amounts of data
• Easier to implement but slower due to system calls for sending/receiving messages
• No conflict needs to be avoided in message passing
• Shared memory is faster, requiring no system calls for reading/writing data
• Shared memory needs protection and synchronization

Title: Microkernel System Structure
Content:
• Applications communicate via interprocess communication
• Uses messages for communication between processes
• Microkernel handles memory management and CPU scheduling
• Device drivers operate in user mode and kernel mode

Title: Advantages of Microkernel
Content:
• Easier to extend the OS by adding new services to user space without kernel modification
• Easier to port the OS to new architectures due to small kernel and fewer changes
• More reliable and secure as most services run as user processes; if a service fails, the rest of the OS remains untouched

Title: Disadvantages of Microkernel
Content:
• Performance overhead due to message passing
• Example comparison: Windows NT uses microkernel, whereas Windows XP has a monolithic kernel

Title: Shared Memory Restrictions
Content:
• One process cannot access another process's memory
• Access is restricted for protection

Title: Producer-Consumer Problem
Content:
• Paradigm for cooperating processes
• Producer creates information consumed by a consumer
• Uses a buffer to contain data items
• Utilizes shared memory for buffer and variables

Title: Bounded-Buffer Solution Overview
Content:
• Shared memory solution for producer-consumer problem
• Producer and consumer access a shared buffer
• Addresses synchronization issues in concurrent access
• Referenced in Chapters 6 and 7

Title: Message-Passing Operations
Content:
• Two main operations: send(message) 
• Two main operations: receive(message)

Title: Synchronous vs Asynchronous
Content:
• Message passing can be blocking or non-blocking
• Blocking: process suspended until I/O is completed; easy to use but insufficient for some needs
• Non-blocking: I/O call returns immediately with available data; includes return value indicating number of bytes transferred

Title: Blocking and Non-Blocking I/O
Content:
• Blocking is synchronous
• Blocking send: sender blocked until message received
• Blocking receive: receiver blocked until message available
• Non-blocking is asynchronous
• Non-blocking send: sender sends message and resumes operation
• Non-blocking receive: receiver retrieves valid message or null

Title: POSIX Shared Memory Functions
Content:
• shm_open(): create or open a shared memory object
• mmap(): memory map the shared memory object; access the shared memory as ordinary memory
• shmunlink(): remove the shared memory object

Title: POSIX Shared Memory Overview
Content:
• Process creation for shared memory involves functions like 'open' and 'ftruncate'
• Memory mapping done using 'mmap' with specified protection and sharing attributes
• Data can be written and formatted using 'sprintf' on the mapped memory
